{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17641499","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17641499"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:27:27+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:27:27+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17880"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17880","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17880"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10594"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115333"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10594","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10594"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17880"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97336"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10053"},{"type":"tags","id":"10061"},{"type":"tags","id":"10063"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24692"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24694"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115333","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115333"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following statements regarding the regulation of pyruvate dehydrogenase (PDH) is correct?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["PDH is activated by phosphorylation by pyruvate dehydrogenase kinases (PDKs)","PDH is a multi-enzyme complex that links glycolysis to the citric acid cycle","Activation of PDH favours fatty acid oxidation","PDH is inactivated by pyruvate dehydrogenase phosphatases","PDH regulation does not affect substrate selection for oxidative phosphorylation"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPDH is a multi-enzyme complex that links glycolysis to the citric acid cycle\u003C/strong\u003E. It catalyses the conversion of pyruvate to acetyl-CoA, a critical step in cellular respiration.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPDH is activated by phosphorylation by pyruvate dehydrogenase kinases (PDKs)\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. PDH is actually inactivated by phosphorylation by PDKs. Dephosphorylation by pyruvate dehydrogenase phosphatases activates PDH.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EActivation of PDH favours fatty acid oxidation\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. Activation of PDH favours glucose oxidation, as it facilitates the conversion of pyruvate (from glycolysis) to acetyl-CoA for entry into the citric acid cycle.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPDH is inactivated by pyruvate dehydrogenase phosphatases\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. PDH is activated by dephosphorylation by pyruvate dehydrogenase phosphatases.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPDH regulation does not affect substrate selection for oxidative phosphorylation\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. PDH regulation is a determinant of substrate selection, as it influences whether glucose or fatty acids are used for energy production.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Pyruvate dehydrogenase (PDH) is a multi-enzyme complex that is essential in the linking of glycolysis to the citric acid cycle.","PDH is regulated by phosphorylation; it is inactivated by pyruvate dehydrogenase kinases (PDKs) and activated by pyruvate dehydrogenase phosphatases.","Activation of PDH favours glucose oxidation over fatty acid oxidation."],"references":["Hall JE. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2021. Chapter 68, pg. 846.","Bender DA, Cunningham SM. Introduction to nutrition and metabolism. CRC Press; 2021.","Salway JG. Metabolism at a Glance. John Wiley \u0026 Sons; 2016.","Chandel NS. Amino Acid Metabolism. Cold Spring Harb Perspect Biol. 2021 Apr 1;13(4):a040584. doi: 10.1101/cshperspect.a040584. PMID: 33795250; PMCID: PMC8015690.","Ling ZN, Jiang YF, Ru JN, Lu JH, Ding B, Wu J. Amino acid metabolism in health and disease. Signal Transduct Target Ther. 2023 Sep 13;8(1):345. doi: 10.1038/s41392-023-01569-3. PMID: 37699892; PMCID: PMC10497558."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97336"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17880"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97336","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97336"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-23T12:21:16+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-23T12:21:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10594"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115333"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":nu